1
00:00:06,000 --> 00:00:12,074
-== [ www.OpenSubtitles.com ] ==-

2
00:02:24,895 --> 00:02:27,830
Can somebody tell me
what's going on?

3
00:02:27,898 --> 00:02:29,695
Don't be foolish, Walter.
Get him back to bed.

4
00:02:29,766 --> 00:02:31,393
- Bar the door.
- I'm still the master of this house.

5
00:02:31,468 --> 00:02:32,867
Richard, up.

6
00:02:35,572 --> 00:02:37,039
Who is there?

7
00:02:37,607 --> 00:02:38,699
Wake up, Thomas.

8
00:02:44,381 --> 00:02:45,905
Open the gates!

9
00:02:55,625 --> 00:02:56,887
Bastards.

10
00:02:57,727 --> 00:02:58,887
Arrow.

11
00:03:02,999 --> 00:03:04,398
The lantern.

12
00:03:15,112 --> 00:03:16,943
I see you, you little bastards.

13
00:03:17,547 --> 00:03:18,878
I see you!

14
00:03:31,628 --> 00:03:33,255
Thieving maggots.

15
00:03:33,763 --> 00:03:36,163
They've taken all our seed grain.

16
00:03:36,933 --> 00:03:39,527
What are we going to do for planting?

17
00:03:40,370 --> 00:03:41,462
Pray.

18
00:04:46,269 --> 00:04:47,736
Hello, there!

19
00:05:00,817 --> 00:05:03,342
- Here you go, lad.
- Thank you, Robin.

20
00:05:03,820 --> 00:05:04,980
Robin.

21
00:05:05,522 --> 00:05:06,887
The archers been called to ranks.

22
00:05:06,957 --> 00:05:08,857
Bloody typical.
I'm starving.

23
00:05:10,260 --> 00:05:11,488
Hide these well.

24
00:05:11,861 --> 00:05:14,352
We'll have them for supper instead.

25
00:05:31,014 --> 00:05:32,106
Sire.

26
00:05:33,416 --> 00:05:35,008
Your bath, Sire.

27
00:05:53,003 --> 00:05:55,665
For the love of Christ, Loxley,
would you stop them doing that!

28
00:05:55,739 --> 00:05:57,263
They love you, Sire.

29
00:05:57,340 --> 00:05:59,934
My head. It's going like
the bells of hell.

30
00:06:02,879 --> 00:06:03,971
Is that it?

31
00:06:04,047 --> 00:06:08,450
One more castle to sack,
then we're home to England.

32
00:06:09,653 --> 00:06:11,814
Hail King Richard!

33
00:06:17,060 --> 00:06:18,288
Release!

34
00:06:18,695 --> 00:06:19,957
Push!

35
00:06:21,264 --> 00:06:22,629
Push!

36
00:06:23,800 --> 00:06:25,199
Hey, archer!

37
00:06:25,602 --> 00:06:26,864
Stay alive!

38
00:06:26,936 --> 00:06:28,130
I'll see you tonight.

39
00:06:28,438 --> 00:06:30,269
Don't forget your money this time,
little man.

40
00:06:30,340 --> 00:06:32,365
It will be my pleasure
to take it off you.

41
00:06:34,244 --> 00:06:35,336
Push!

42
00:06:40,050 --> 00:06:41,278
Move up!

43
00:06:46,823 --> 00:06:48,882
Cover the King!
Cover the King!

44
00:06:52,762 --> 00:06:54,889
Barricades prepare!

45
00:07:03,707 --> 00:07:05,732
Let us put these French to bed!

46
00:07:10,180 --> 00:07:12,239
Raise the barricades!

47
00:07:25,295 --> 00:07:26,489
Jimmy.

48
00:07:26,996 --> 00:07:28,827
Calm and careful.
Make it count.

49
00:07:29,099 --> 00:07:30,123
Go!

50
00:07:53,022 --> 00:07:54,011
Help!

51
00:07:55,692 --> 00:07:56,852
Cover!

52
00:08:08,671 --> 00:08:09,729
Now.

53
00:08:13,176 --> 00:08:14,200
Go!

54
00:08:23,520 --> 00:08:24,851
Move back!

55
00:08:26,289 --> 00:08:28,018
Blood for France!

56
00:08:29,826 --> 00:08:30,850
Go!

57
00:08:32,295 --> 00:08:34,195
It'll make a fine pin cushion!

58
00:08:34,264 --> 00:08:36,289
King Philip's arse!

59
00:08:50,480 --> 00:08:53,108
Look what they do
for the Lion Heart!

60
00:08:53,183 --> 00:08:56,243
Look what they do
for the Lion Heart!

61
00:08:59,155 --> 00:09:00,247
Push!

62
00:09:00,890 --> 00:09:02,221
Push!

63
00:09:02,292 --> 00:09:05,318
That'll burn all night, lads.
Don't let them put it out.

64
00:09:05,395 --> 00:09:08,853
These pricks will smash through
in the morning, take all the credit.

65
00:09:08,932 --> 00:09:10,456
Well done, Jimmy boy.

66
00:09:31,554 --> 00:09:32,782
John...

67
00:09:32,856 --> 00:09:34,323
Your Majesty.

68
00:09:34,958 --> 00:09:37,984
An English princess shut out
of her husband's bedchamber

69
00:09:38,061 --> 00:09:40,222
by a piece of French pastry!

70
00:09:40,296 --> 00:09:41,820
Aren't you ashamed?

71
00:09:41,898 --> 00:09:43,763
The shame is surely his.

72
00:09:43,833 --> 00:09:45,824
Then go in and tell him.

73
00:09:45,902 --> 00:09:49,531
Mewling at his keyhole
is neither one thing nor the other.

74
00:09:50,673 --> 00:09:51,765
John.

75
00:09:57,180 --> 00:09:58,943
Oh, God! What in heaven...

76
00:09:59,015 --> 00:10:03,349
<i>Mademoiselle,</i> you will excuse me.
My son has need of my advice.

77
00:10:03,419 --> 00:10:05,216
No, I don't. Ask her.

78
00:10:07,357 --> 00:10:09,052
Mother, please, have you no decency?

79
00:10:09,125 --> 00:10:13,687
I happen to be in a condition
that no mother should see her son in.

80
00:10:17,534 --> 00:10:20,401
- Yes, I know, but it's my mother.
- That's enough.

81
00:10:20,470 --> 00:10:25,169
On second thoughts, I think it better
that you do hear what I have to say.

82
00:10:25,241 --> 00:10:28,074
Though I will not have you
in my presence.

83
00:10:28,778 --> 00:10:29,802
Mother.

84
00:10:29,879 --> 00:10:33,781
The purpose of my being in this room
is to save the realm

85
00:10:33,850 --> 00:10:37,946
from the consequences
of this unsuitable amusement.

86
00:10:38,021 --> 00:10:40,717
Her uncle is the bloody King of France.

87
00:10:41,891 --> 00:10:43,859
- My uncle is...
- Get down.

88
00:10:44,594 --> 00:10:46,585
Her uncle wants her back.

89
00:10:47,030 --> 00:10:50,363
Philip wants an excuse to cross

90
00:10:52,735 --> 00:10:54,532
the Channel with an army.

91
00:10:54,604 --> 00:10:57,198
And you have given him that excuse.

92
00:10:58,174 --> 00:11:01,143
Take up your lawful wife
and save England.

93
00:11:01,210 --> 00:11:04,873
My lawful wife
is as barren as a brick.

94
00:11:05,214 --> 00:11:07,910
Is that truly the wife
you want for me?

95
00:11:08,351 --> 00:11:09,511
Hmm?

96
00:11:09,586 --> 00:11:12,885
You, who honored your husband
with eight children

97
00:11:12,956 --> 00:11:15,516
so that even now
when death has taken the rest

98
00:11:15,592 --> 00:11:20,552
you have a king and the runt
of the litter to call you "Mother."

99
00:11:21,064 --> 00:11:23,328
Better the bastard of a servant girl

100
00:11:23,399 --> 00:11:25,959
than bed the niece
of England's jealous enemy.

101
00:11:26,035 --> 00:11:28,629
Or bed her and wed her, Mother.

102
00:11:28,705 --> 00:11:31,333
I've asked the Pope's men
to arrange an annulment.

103
00:11:31,407 --> 00:11:33,170
And do you think the Pope

104
00:11:33,242 --> 00:11:36,837
will favor England's royal runt
over the King of France?

105
00:11:36,913 --> 00:11:40,007
He might see his way for the son
of Eleanor of Aquitaine.

106
00:11:40,116 --> 00:11:42,516
And for the future King of England.

107
00:11:42,585 --> 00:11:46,385
Richard the Lion Heart
is 40-years-old, if not more.

108
00:11:47,657 --> 00:11:49,147
And no babies.

109
00:11:50,393 --> 00:11:52,452
I am a queen in the making.

110
00:11:54,731 --> 00:11:56,460
Yes. Yes.

111
00:11:58,134 --> 00:11:59,362
You see?

112
00:12:00,570 --> 00:12:02,902
She is my Eleanor.

113
00:12:06,142 --> 00:12:09,543
Now, you do understand,
this game is not about luck.

114
00:12:09,612 --> 00:12:12,547
It's about the science of memory
and a quick hand.

115
00:12:12,615 --> 00:12:14,310
Who'd like to take
a bit of fresh meat home?

116
00:12:14,384 --> 00:12:16,477
Caught this morning.
We have a pheasant.

117
00:12:16,552 --> 00:12:19,077
Three choices.
Right, left or middle?

118
00:12:19,155 --> 00:12:20,247
Middle.

119
00:12:20,323 --> 00:12:22,757
"The middle," he says.
The middle.

120
00:12:22,825 --> 00:12:26,852
I'm sorry about those onions,
young man. You lose.

121
00:12:26,929 --> 00:12:28,487
Robin! Over here,
they're needed for the pot.

122
00:12:28,564 --> 00:12:29,997
Feisty one!

123
00:12:30,900 --> 00:12:33,630
Aye, what else we got,
what else we got?

124
00:12:33,703 --> 00:12:35,364
The fire will do its work.

125
00:12:35,438 --> 00:12:38,032
We break through at first light.

126
00:12:38,107 --> 00:12:41,770
With a fair wind,
we can be home in three days.

127
00:12:43,046 --> 00:12:44,274
You return to Nottingham?

128
00:12:45,014 --> 00:12:48,142
I have a wife who waits for me.

129
00:12:49,485 --> 00:12:52,113
I have a mother that won't die

130
00:12:52,789 --> 00:12:54,882
and a brother who wishes me dead.

131
00:12:54,957 --> 00:12:57,551
First thing I'm going to do
is lock them up.

132
00:12:57,627 --> 00:13:00,323
Your people will rejoice
to see you return home.

133
00:13:00,396 --> 00:13:02,990
And that is a condition
I would like to keep them in.

134
00:13:03,066 --> 00:13:05,091
To be remembered as I was.

135
00:13:07,203 --> 00:13:08,295
My army knows better.

136
00:13:10,873 --> 00:13:13,364
Lion Heart is mangy.

137
00:13:14,010 --> 00:13:18,106
Every man in that army idolizes you,
Your Majesty.

138
00:13:18,181 --> 00:13:19,978
Don't mollycoddle me.

139
00:13:21,084 --> 00:13:24,645
I understand how difficult it must be
to befriend a king.

140
00:13:25,421 --> 00:13:29,255
Come on, Loxley.
Let us find some ruffians, drink and laugh.

141
00:13:30,193 --> 00:13:32,855
Let us see if we can find
an honest man.

142
00:13:32,929 --> 00:13:34,055
Yes.

143
00:13:35,098 --> 00:13:36,122
Let's do that.

144
00:13:47,310 --> 00:13:50,108
Well, that's the thing, little man.
This is not a game of luck.

145
00:13:50,179 --> 00:13:53,546
It's about the science of memory
and a quick hand.

146
00:13:53,616 --> 00:13:57,484
I've got a quick eye.
I'll be watching you.

147
00:14:09,932 --> 00:14:11,593
Three choices.

148
00:14:11,667 --> 00:14:13,999
Right, left, or middle.

149
00:14:15,471 --> 00:14:17,905
I think I'll take a fourth choice.

150
00:14:18,875 --> 00:14:20,866
- A fourth?
- Hmm.

151
00:14:20,943 --> 00:14:24,037
I've been watching you
for a while now, Longstride.

152
00:14:24,113 --> 00:14:26,445
There is no pea.

153
00:14:27,583 --> 00:14:29,881
This game is a trick!

154
00:14:29,952 --> 00:14:34,082
You take out the pea when you're doing
your slidings and your turnings.

155
00:14:34,157 --> 00:14:35,488
I got you.

156
00:14:40,663 --> 00:14:42,460
Don't touch it again.

157
00:14:43,366 --> 00:14:44,731
I'll do it!

158
00:15:05,788 --> 00:15:07,050
You lose.

159
00:15:26,042 --> 00:15:27,634
You're doing better than you think.

160
00:15:27,710 --> 00:15:29,473
Get in there, Robin.

161
00:15:38,888 --> 00:15:41,652
Kneel, you ignorant bastards!

162
00:15:41,724 --> 00:15:43,589
Kneel before the King!

163
00:15:46,095 --> 00:15:47,790
All of you, move back, now.

164
00:15:47,864 --> 00:15:51,960
No, no, Loxley.
These men are soldiers at play.

165
00:15:52,034 --> 00:15:54,229
Sinners after mine own heart.

166
00:15:55,071 --> 00:15:57,562
Which one of you started the fight?

167
00:15:59,876 --> 00:16:01,275
I did, Sire.

168
00:16:02,645 --> 00:16:04,704
I threw the first punch.

169
00:16:04,780 --> 00:16:06,145
Ah, honest man.

170
00:16:07,116 --> 00:16:08,413
And who're you fighting?

171
00:16:09,685 --> 00:16:12,518
He was fighting me, Your Majesty.

172
00:16:12,588 --> 00:16:14,749
I thought him to be a lesser man.

173
00:16:15,658 --> 00:16:17,285
He was showing me different.

174
00:16:18,995 --> 00:16:21,327
An enemy that shows his respect.

175
00:16:21,931 --> 00:16:24,229
Stand up, the pair of you.

176
00:16:24,300 --> 00:16:25,528
Not you.

177
00:16:30,306 --> 00:16:33,139
Brave and honest.

178
00:16:34,577 --> 00:16:39,241
Are you honest enough to tell a king
something that he does not want to hear?

179
00:16:39,615 --> 00:16:42,106
What is your opinion on my crusade?

180
00:16:44,453 --> 00:16:47,752
Will God be pleased with my sacrifice?

181
00:16:57,233 --> 00:16:58,700
No, he won't.

182
00:17:00,503 --> 00:17:02,266
Why do you say that?

183
00:17:03,105 --> 00:17:05,198
The massacre at Acre, Sire.

184
00:17:06,208 --> 00:17:07,470
Speak up!

185
00:17:09,412 --> 00:17:13,940
When you had us herd 2,500 Muslim men,
women, and children together,

186
00:17:14,016 --> 00:17:18,282
the young woman at my feet,
with her hands bound, she looked up at me.

187
00:17:19,188 --> 00:17:22,351
There wasn't fear in her eyes.
There wasn't anger.

188
00:17:23,292 --> 00:17:25,055
There was only pity.

189
00:17:27,596 --> 00:17:30,429
For she knew that
when you gave the order

190
00:17:31,434 --> 00:17:34,528
and our blades
would descend upon their heads,

191
00:17:35,004 --> 00:17:37,734
that, in that moment,
we would be godless.

192
00:17:38,541 --> 00:17:39,872
All of us.

193
00:17:42,244 --> 00:17:43,472
Godless.

194
00:17:48,117 --> 00:17:49,311
Honest,

195
00:17:50,619 --> 00:17:51,711
brave

196
00:17:52,955 --> 00:17:54,286
and naïve.

197
00:17:56,459 --> 00:17:58,654
There is your Englishman.

198
00:17:59,729 --> 00:18:01,128
Right there.

199
00:18:03,466 --> 00:18:05,900
- Well done, Robin.
- You showed him.

200
00:18:06,369 --> 00:18:07,859
The whipping will be
the worst of it.

201
00:18:07,970 --> 00:18:09,335
The branding iron,
that will be the worst.

202
00:18:09,405 --> 00:18:10,599
Unless they hang us.

203
00:18:10,673 --> 00:18:13,233
No. No, this will be the worst of it.

204
00:18:13,309 --> 00:18:17,643
And this will be the end of it.
As soon as I get out of here, I'm gone.

205
00:18:18,280 --> 00:18:21,943
I don't owe God or any other man here
one more minute of service.

206
00:19:22,945 --> 00:19:25,778
We go all the way back
to the same breast.

207
00:19:28,050 --> 00:19:29,312
Wet nurse.

208
00:19:29,385 --> 00:19:30,579
Indeed.

209
00:19:32,354 --> 00:19:33,514
We've been close ever since.

210
00:19:35,658 --> 00:19:36,784
Good.

211
00:19:39,195 --> 00:19:42,426
Because England,
under your friend John,

212
00:19:43,933 --> 00:19:46,527
is a country with no fighting spirit.

213
00:19:47,236 --> 00:19:49,966
I can take London
with an army of cooks.

214
00:19:50,806 --> 00:19:53,104
But Richard is on his way home.

215
00:19:53,809 --> 00:19:57,973
And under Richard,
England is a different animal altogether.

216
00:19:58,814 --> 00:20:02,215
Richard will return home
through the Forest of Broceliande.

217
00:20:03,285 --> 00:20:05,253
We know the exact place.

218
00:20:05,788 --> 00:20:11,727
He always travels ahead of his army
with only a few trusted knights around him.

219
00:20:13,028 --> 00:20:17,226
With Richard dead, it will be easy for you
to turn the country against John.

220
00:20:18,134 --> 00:20:20,364
There'll never be
a better moment to invade.

221
00:20:24,907 --> 00:20:27,432
Even dying animals can be obstinate.

222
00:20:30,513 --> 00:20:33,448
Kill the Lion Heart
and you will be richly rewarded.

223
00:20:52,134 --> 00:20:53,294
Heave!

224
00:20:54,670 --> 00:20:55,830
Heave!

225
00:21:12,388 --> 00:21:13,548
Heave!

226
00:21:14,557 --> 00:21:16,149
For England!

227
00:21:20,896 --> 00:21:22,295
For England!

228
00:21:32,041 --> 00:21:33,702
I need a physician here!

229
00:21:33,776 --> 00:21:35,744
A physician! Quickly!

230
00:21:35,811 --> 00:21:37,506
Give us cover!
Give us cover, now!

231
00:21:40,916 --> 00:21:41,940
Cover him!

232
00:21:43,385 --> 00:21:44,443
Cover the King.

233
00:21:45,254 --> 00:21:47,484
Physician!

234
00:21:48,524 --> 00:21:50,082
Why, Loxley?
Are you not feeling well?

235
00:21:50,459 --> 00:21:52,256
Physician!

236
00:21:58,667 --> 00:21:59,759
Wine.

237
00:22:22,858 --> 00:22:24,257
What's this?

238
00:22:25,427 --> 00:22:27,588
- The King is dead!
- Dead?

239
00:22:28,397 --> 00:22:29,489
Dead.

240
00:22:29,865 --> 00:22:34,529
All right, then, Jimmy. Knock the pegs out.
We make our own fate from now on!

241
00:22:38,073 --> 00:22:39,438
I'll come with you.

242
00:22:39,508 --> 00:22:42,443
No, you're not.
We don't take strays.

243
00:22:42,511 --> 00:22:43,535
The more the merrier.

244
00:22:43,612 --> 00:22:45,546
The road will be dangerous.
He might be useful.

245
00:22:45,614 --> 00:22:46,638
Where we going?

246
00:22:46,715 --> 00:22:50,344
To the coast and to a boat
before 3,000 desperate soldiers get there

247
00:22:50,419 --> 00:22:52,819
and the price for a Channel crossing
goes up a hundredfold.

248
00:22:52,888 --> 00:22:54,253
What about our wages?

249
00:22:54,323 --> 00:22:57,383
If you thought it was hard getting wages
while he was alive,

250
00:22:57,459 --> 00:22:59,324
try getting paid by a dead king.

251
00:22:59,395 --> 00:23:02,592
All right, boys,
collect your gear as quick as you can.

252
00:23:08,370 --> 00:23:10,235
I like the new church.

253
00:23:13,342 --> 00:23:14,673
Lady Marion.

254
00:23:14,743 --> 00:23:20,045
I would have been sorry to leave
without your farewell. Thank you.

255
00:23:21,116 --> 00:23:23,550
I'm glad to speed you on your way,
Father Tancred,

256
00:23:23,619 --> 00:23:26,986
but it was to seek out
our new shepherd.

257
00:23:27,056 --> 00:23:31,516
You have lately been missed
at Sunday worship and my sermons.

258
00:23:32,328 --> 00:23:36,264
I like a quiet church, Father,
when I pray for a miracle.

259
00:23:43,472 --> 00:23:47,602
Your new flock is women,
children and old folk.

260
00:23:47,676 --> 00:23:49,837
Our men have gone to war
or returned broken.

261
00:23:50,279 --> 00:23:53,009
Their orphans run wild
in the greenwood.

262
00:23:56,552 --> 00:23:59,851
Our fields are ready for planting
but we've no seed corn.

263
00:24:00,255 --> 00:24:03,053
